<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rob. Fernandez, I. Revilla &amp; E. Pariente" authorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Saracha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saracha andina" order="Solanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Saracha andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other species of the genus in its small oblong to broadly elliptic leaves 12-27 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-14 mm with inconspicuous nerves and tubular flowers 33.5-35 mm long. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. punctata" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="punctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">S. punctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has elliptic leaves 20-150 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-60 mm and widely campanulate flowers, and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. quitensis" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="quitensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">S. quitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has shorter tubular to infundibuliform flowers 12-26 mm long (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Saracha species. A Saracha punctata (R. Fernandez et al. 260; MOL) B Saracha quitensis (S. Smith 257; MO) C Saracha andina (P. Gonzales et al. 3385; USM) D Saracha andina (R. Fernandez et al. 973; MOL) E Saracha punctata (R. Fernandez 998; MOL) F Saracha quitensis (S. Smith 257; MO) G Saracha andina (R. Fernandez et al. 973; MOL). Photos by: A, D, E, G Robin Fernandez; B, F Stacey Smith; C Paul Gonzales." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.85.12607.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/149348" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">3</figureCitation>
). Among other members of the subtribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Iochrominae">Iochrominae</taxonomicName>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Olmstead, RG" editor="Nee, M" journalOrPublisher="Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="111 - 137" refId="B36" refString="Olmstead, RG, Sweere, JA, Spangler, RE, Bohs, L, Palmer, JD, 1999. Phylogeny and provisional classification of the Solanaceae based on chloroplast DNA. In: Nee, M, Symon, DE, Lester, RN, Jessop, JP, Eds., Solanaceae IV: advances in biology and utilization. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew: 111 - 137" title="Phylogeny and provisional classification of the Solanaceae based on chloroplast DNA." volumeTitle="Solanaceae IV: advances in biology and utilization." year="1999">Olmstead et al. (1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Olmstead, RG" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" pagination="1159 - 1181" refId="B37" refString="Olmstead, RG, Bohs, L, Migid, H, Santiago-Valentin, E, Garcia, V, Collier, S, 2008. A molecular phylogeny of the Solanaceae. Taxon 57 (4): 1159 - 1181" title="A molecular phylogeny of the Solanaceae." volume="57" year="2008">2008</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. andina" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">S. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is perhaps most easily confused with species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Dunalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dunalia" order="Solanales" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Dunalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, many of which have tubular flowers of similar 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="36" start="start">length</pageBreakToken>
and the plants are spiny (see discussion in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399334" author="D'Arcy, WG" journalOrPublisher="Academic Press, London" pageId="6" pageNumber="37" refId="B12" refString="D'Arcy, WG, Smith, DN, 1987. https://doi.org/10.2307/2399334" url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399334" year="1987">
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Arcy">D'Arcy</normalizedToken>
and Smith 1987
</bibRefCitation>
). Nonetheless, species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Dunalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dunalia" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Dunalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a diagnostic pair of appendages on either side of the filament base (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“stapet”">&quot;stapet&quot;</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Hunziker, AT" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" pagination="211 - 244" refId="B19" refString="Hunziker, AT, 1960. Estudios sobre Solanaceae II. Sinopsis taxonomica del genero Dunalia H. B. K. Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias 51: 211 - 244" title="Estudios sobre Solanaceae II. Sinopsis taxonomica del genero Dunalia H. B. K." volume="51" year="1960">Hunziker 1960</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hunziker, AT" journalOrPublisher="ARG Ganter Verlag KG, Koenigstein" pageId="7" pageNumber="38" refId="B20" refString="Hunziker, AT, 2001. Genera Solanacearum: The Genera of Solanaceae Illustrated, Arranged According to a New System. ARG Ganter Verlag KG, Koenigstein" title="Genera Solanacearum: The Genera of Solanaceae Illustrated, Arranged According to a New System." year="2001">2001</bibRefCitation>
), and sometimes the leaves clustered on short shoots but they lack the conspicuous coriaceous leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Saracha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saracha" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="36">Saracha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
